// FAQ data
const faqs = [
  {
    question: "What does RV insurance actually cover?",
    answer: "RV insurance covers liability (if you cause an accident), collision (damage from crashes), comprehensive (theft, weather, vandalism), personal belongings inside, and often roadside assistance. Full-timer policies add coverage for your RV as a residence—liability for guests, higher personal property limits, and loss-of-use coverage."
  },
  {
    question: "Do I really need specialized RV insurance?",
    answer: "Yes. Standard auto insurance doesn't properly cover RVs. RVs have unique risks—higher values, living quarters, specialized components—that auto policies don't address. Even a travel trailer needs its own policy, not just whatever your tow vehicle has."
  },
  {
    question: "What's the difference between full-timer and recreational coverage?",
    answer: "Recreational policies cover RVs you use occasionally for trips. Full-timer policies treat your RV as your primary residence, adding coverage for personal belongings (like renters insurance), liability for guests visiting your 'home,' and higher property limits. If you live in your RV more than 6 months/year, you need full-timer coverage."
  },
  {
    question: "How much does RV insurance cost?",
    answer: "Recreational RV insurance runs $500-$2,000/year depending on RV type and value. Full-timer policies cost $1,500-$4,000/year. Class A motorhomes cost more to insure than travel trailers. Location, driving history, and coverage levels also affect premiums significantly."
  },
  {
    question: "What's 'agreed value' vs 'actual cash value'?",
    answer: "Actual cash value pays what your RV is worth today (with depreciation). Agreed value pays a predetermined amount you and the insurer agree on when you buy the policy. For newer or well-maintained RVs, agreed value protects your investment better—you know exactly what you'll get if it's totaled."
  },
  {
    question: "Does my auto insurance cover my RV at all?",
    answer: "Your auto insurance might cover liability while towing a trailer, but it won't cover the RV itself. Motorhomes definitely need their own policy. Even towable RVs need separate coverage for comprehensive, collision, and contents. Never assume your auto policy is enough."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I insure my RV if I rent it out?",
    answer: "Standard RV policies exclude commercial use, including rentals. If you rent through Outdoorsy or RVShare, their platform insurance covers rentals, but verify the limits. For frequent rentals, you'll need a commercial RV policy or the rental platform's insurance add-ons."
  }
];
