        <div class="bg-[#EFF6FF] p-6 rounded-xl border border-blue-200">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-[#1E40AF] mb-2">Full-Timer vs. Recreational</h3>
          <p>If you live in your RV more than 6 months/year, you need full-timer coverage. It adds liability for your RV as a residence, higher personal property limits, and loss-of-use coverage if your home gets damaged.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[#F8FAFC] p-6 rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-[#162433] mb-2">Agreed Value vs. Actual Cash Value</h3>
          <p>Agreed value pays a predetermined amount if your RV is totaled. Actual cash value deducts depreciation. For newer or custom RVs, agreed value protects your investment—you won't get lowballed when you've invested serious money.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[#F8FAFC] p-6 rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-[#162433] mb-2">Consider Your RV Type</h3>
          <p>Class A motorhomes cost more to insure than travel trailers. Fifth wheels cost more than pop-ups. Make sure your policy covers the actual replacement cost of your specific RV type.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[#F8FAFC] p-6 rounded-xl">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-[#162433] mb-2">Check Roadside Assistance Details</h3>
          <p>RVs need specialized towing—not every tow truck can handle a 40-foot motorhome. Make sure roadside assistance includes heavy-duty towing and RV-specific services.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

